# TikTok Tech Immersion 2023

![Tests](https://github.com/sanstzu/tiktok-tech-immersion-2023/actions/workflows/test.yml/badge.svg)

*This repository is based on the template given from the forked repository as a part of one of the assignments in TikTok Tech Immersion 2023.*

## Overview
This repository contains a basic implementation of an Instant Messaging (IM) system which consists of a HTTP server and RPC server. It was made using Golang, Kitex RPC Framework and MySQL Database.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

There are two endpoints in the HTTP server:
- `/api/pull`

    `GET` request to retrieve messages from a particular sender and recipient with the following query:
    | **Query** | **Details** | **Example** |
    |---|---|---|
    | `chat` | In the format of `sender:recipient`.|`brian:peter`
    | `cursor` | The starting point (in Unix Timestamp Microsecond) of the pulled messages,  inclusively. Default value is `0`. | `1686059804000000`
    | `limit` | The number of messages that would be retrieved. Default value is `10`. | `10` |
    | `reverse` | If `false`, the messages will be sorted ascendingly. Default value is `true`.| `true` |
    
    The URL for the GET request would be `localhost:8080/api/pull?chat=peter%3Abrian&cursor=1686059804000000&limit=10&reverse=true`.

    This will return a JSON an array of `message` struct:
    ```json
        {
            "chat": string,
            "text": string,
            "sender": string,
            "send_time": int64,
        }
    ```
    
    However if the number of messages after the `cursor` is larger than `limit`, then it would also return `next_cursor` alongside the array of JSON, which is the `timestamp+1` of the last message.

- `/api/send`

    `POST` request to send message from a sender to a recipient with the following parameter:
    | **Parameter** | **Details** | **Example** |
    |---|---|---|
    | `sender` | The sender name/username. |`brian`|
    | `receiver` |The recipient name/username. | `peter`|
    | `text` | The content of the message | `Peter, what are you doing?` |

    The URL for the POST request would be `localhost:8080/api/send?sender=brian&receiver=peter&text=Peter,%20what%20are%20you%20doing?`

    If the message was successfully sent, there would not be any response aside from the `200 OK` response.

## Setup
1. Cloning the repository
    ```
    git clone https://github.com/sanstzu/tiktok-tech-immersion-2023
    ```

2. Build the Docker container inside the repository folder
    ```
    docker-compose up --build
    ```

3. Once it is build, the four images should be running and the endpoint should be accessible. To test, simply open the URL/perform a `GET` request on `localhost:8080/ping`, which should return:
    ```json
    {
        "message": "pong"
    }
    ```
